rio, Maurizio, Nichola, Nicola, Severino, Vittorio.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of   Albino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Manuel, Ana, Carlos, Julio, Luis, Raul, Ruben, Alfonso, Andres, Angel.  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Giovanni, Luigi, Sal, Santo, Saverio, Ubalda.","Portuguese, Spanish, and southern Italian:","from the personal name <i>Albino</i> (see   Albin  )."]}]},{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is probably derived from the surname. In England this surname is found mainly in the West Midlands; it has also spread into Wales. In Ireland this form is common in Ulster; MacLysaght records that it was taken there from England in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Memory","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Albini Mowbray was born about 1210, in Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Albini de Mowbray, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. William Mowbray, was 28. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Walter Mowbray. He died about 1252, in his hometown, at the age of 44."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1210–aproximadamente 1252":"umbes 1210–umbes 1252","1210–1252":"1210–1252","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","aproximadamente 1210":"umbes 1210","aproximadamente 1252":"umbes 1252","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1184":"1184","aproximadamente 1235":"umbes 1235","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Easby, Yorkshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Easby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"aproximadamente 1210–aproximadamente 1252":"noin 1210–noin 1252","1210–1252":"1210–1252","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1184–Female":"1184–Kuollut","aproximadamente 1210":"noin 1210","aproximadamente 1252":"noin 1252","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1184":"1184","aproximadamente 1235":"noin 1235","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Easby, Yorkshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Easby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"aproximadamente 1210–aproximadamente 1252":"environ 1210–environ 1252","1210–1252":"1210–1252","1214–Female":"1214–Décédée","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1184–Female":"1184–Décédée","aproximadamente 1210":"environ 1210","aproximadamente 1252":"environ 1252","1214":"1